<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-499-523  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 499 523.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Sept 17 1990 v7 n38 p27(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Eastern Europe to benefit from relaxed export rules.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crockett, Barton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls(COCOM) is adopting more lenient export rules, making it easierfor users and vendors to import advanced communications andcomputer equipment into Eastern European countries.andP;  Users can nowbring any computer into the Eastern bloc countries with the powerequivalent to a 33-MHz Intel Corp 80386-based IBM PS/2 Model 70 or80.andP;  Most restrictions on token-ring and Ethernet networks arebeing removed and local networks that support speeds of up to20M-bits/second are now allowed.andP;  There are also fewerrestrictions on local network configurations.andP;  Most restrictionson satellite earth station equipment and on modems witherror-correction capabilities are also being dropped.andP;  However,users still need a special license to transport packet-switchingequipment into most Eastern European countries.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic: ; Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsExportEastern EuropePolicyTechnology TransferCommunications EquipmentComputer SystemsLocal Area Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>